This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Science sub-category of Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) as it deals with malware detection and the prevention of damage caused by successful malware attacks. Additionally, the use of machine learning techniques such as convolutional neural networks suggests that it may also belong to the sub-categories of Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Machine Learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the practical limitations of examining a file's entire contents, which suggests that it may belong to the sub-category of Software Engineering (cs.SE). Finally, the use of data analysis and statistical techniques to predict the likelihood of a file being malicious suggests that it may also belong to the sub-category of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS).
